definition: "Vitamin K refers to a family of fat-soluble vitamins that share a common naphthoquinone ring structure and a critical role in activating carboxylase enzymes that modify specific proteins. There are two major natural forms: Vitamin K1 (phylloquinone), found primarily in leafy green vegetables, and Vitamin K2 (menaquinone), found in fermented foods, animal products, and produced by gut bacteria. The menaquinone family includes multiple subtypes designated by side-chain length: MK-4 (found in meat, eggs, and dairy) and MK-7 (found in natto and some fermented cheeses) are the most studied in humans. K1 preferentially activates clotting factors in the liver. K2 — particularly MK-4 and MK-7 — preferentially activates extrahepatic proteins in bone and vascular tissue. The two most longevity-relevant K2-dependent proteins are osteocalcin (in bone, where activated osteocalcin binds calcium into hydroxyapatite) and matrix Gla protein (MGP, in arterial walls, where activated MGP prevents calcium deposition). A critical testing note: standard blood tests for 'vitamin K' measure primarily vitamin K1 (phylloquinone). Specific serum K2 assays (MK-7 or MK-4) are available at specialty labs but are not offered at major consumer labs including Ulta Lab Tests. The clinically practical alternative is measuring functional markers of K2 activity: uncarboxylated osteocalcin (ucOC) and uncarboxylated MGP (ucMGP) — elevated levels of these inactive forms indicate functional K2 deficiency regardless of dietary intake or serum K1."
why_it_matters: "Vitamin K2 occupies a unique position in longevity biology because it acts directly on two of the most important aging processes: vascular calcification (a primary driver of cardiovascular mortality) and bone density loss (driving fracture risk). Matrix Gla protein (MGP) — the most potent known inhibitor of vascular calcification — requires K2 for activation. Studies in the Rotterdam cohort and multiple subsequent analyses found that higher dietary K2 (but not K1) intake was associated with significantly lower rates of aortic calcification and cardiovascular mortality. Separately, the Japanese ECKO and other trials found that menaquinone supplementation (particularly MK-4 at pharmacological doses) reduced vertebral fracture rates. The mechanistic clarity of K2's role in calcium metabolism — directing calcium into bones while preventing its deposition in arteries — gives it a biological rationale that matches the epidemiological findings. The low K2 content of typical Western diets (high in K1 from vegetables but low in fermented K2 sources), combined with strong evidence for functional deficiency in this population, makes K2 one of the most compelling nutritional targets for longevity."

